title: For Sale/Trade:  New Unused Custom Multicam Ghillie Suit!
postcontent:
This is my Ghillie Suit I made AFTER Sniper School in 2010 for my 2011-2012 Afghanistan Deployment. I took this ghillie suit to Afghanistan and back(minus the hat, used my original hat from sniper), but I was in an SDM role instead of a Sniper role and I did not use it. I am in need of money for a firearm project thus I am selling. It took me over three months to make and I have receipts showing a total investment of over $1,000(I must keep for tax purposes). The ghillie hat was finished this year. The hat and netting were new and professionally sewn on by a local seamstress. It took me 8 hours to put the Jute on the boonie cap.

My total price is less than the price of the materials and seamstress labor alone! Making these is monotonous and time consuming! This is not a cookie cutter ghillie suit that is mass produced; this suit is intended and designed for combat operations. You will not find another one of this quality and in this condition for this price that is made by a US Army Sniper trained soldier; or one that has gone to Afghanistan and back and still in new condition... I worked out all the kinks from my actual Sniper School ghillie suit (pictured). The only thing I did not get around to is cutting air vents into it the hat, jacket and pants before I put the jute on; these things get hot in the summer. . .

This multicam Ghillie suit is NEW! (HAS NOT BEEN THROUGH GHILLIE WASH YET!) It was made from Propper brand jacket and pants! It's way more durable than the issued multicam uniforms. The canvas and netting were professionally sewn (have receipts). All seems have been Shoe-Goo'd and painted! Elbow and knee pads have been installed in the perfect position for sniper crawl. There are a bunch of tan 550 cord tie downs.

Package includes:

Multicam Ghillie Hat - Size: 7 1/4
Multicam Ghillie Jacket - Size: Medium Regular
Multicam Ghillie Trousers - Size: Small Regular Pants fits up to 31" waist.
Comes with used Heavy Duty Dickies suspenders
Black sleeping bag stuff sack that fits all (has a blown seam, but still holds suit fine.)

Note: I took the the field pictures of this ghillie suit last week on Fort Carson. This suit works nearly year round in this area and in Afghanistan. I had just taken the suit out of the stuff sack, it is not normally wrinkled and stiff looking. I highly recommend that you put this suit through a ghillie wash, and remember 70% of your suit in the field should be natural veg! The last picture is myself in 2010 in a ghillie suit of the same design but built from DCUs.

$400 cash or best offer, I am in no rush to sell. I am available weekends and weekdays. I can send larger pictures, production pictures, and will meet for inspections. Please call Nate at REDACTED if you're interested. This item is on ebay for $450+Shipping with many watchers! So please serious inquiries only and no low ball offers.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester 94 for SKS/$600
postcontent:
I got this Pre-64 Winchester 94 a while back as a welcome home gift from Afghanistan. 





Even though I'm not a lever action guy, I kept it with the intent to restore it. For a variety of reasons (the biggest of which is that I'm just not a lever action fan) I never got around to doing anything to it. I did find a replacement top-eject .30-30 barrel for it; there's nothing wrong with the original barrel on it, other than it's in .32 Special (not a problem in itself, but again I'm not a lever action fan; sorry, all my childhood heroes used the M-1 Garand or bolt actions). This would be a great project gun for anyone who is into these old west/cowboy types of weapons. 







The serial number indicates that it was built in 1941. It is mechanically sound (verified by a local gunsmith) although it has a lot of finish wear on the receiver (I understand that this was pretty common with the Winnie 94's). The wood is a little worn in some spots, but seems to be pretty good overall; there are no cracks or splits in it that I can see. There is considerably less bluing worn off the barrel. 

What can I say, it's a 71 year old gun. It's older and it was used, but it was also taken care of. 

I'm assigning a trade value of $600 to this. I'm not trying to overestimate it's worth, but they also don't make these anymore.

Trade interests: 

-S&W model 15 with a 4" heavy barrel .38 Special.

-SKS

-What else do you have? Try me, the worst I'll say is "No thanks".

This trade will be FTF in NC for now. It's the holidays, and with all the lunacy currently going on, I ain't even gonna think about shipping....

Email or text REDACTED for more info/offers.

title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1917 .45 ACP WWI Military Revolver $1250 obo
postcontent: This is an original, “unmolested” WWI Colt Model 1917 U.S. Army Double Action Revolver in standard .45 ACP.  Barrel is marked "COLT D.A. 45" on the left side. Top of barrel reads "COLT'S PT FA. MFG. CO HARTFORD CT. U.S.A..PAT'D AUG. 5 1884. JUNE 5 1900. JULY 4 1905." Bottom of barrel is marked "UNITED STATES PROPERTY." Upper left frame is marked with the Ordnance Department final acceptance mark “GHS”, the unique initials cartouche of Gilbert H. Stewart, a Major in the Army Ordinance Department during WWI and the acting Commander of Springfield Arsenal from January 11, 1918 to March 15, 1918.  The Rampart Colt on the left side of the frame is clear and distinct.   The “H” acceptance mark from Frances L. Hosmer (a civilian inspector from 1911 through 1925) is present on the rear of the cylinder and inside the crane recess. The left grip frame is also marked with a “G” signifying “government contract.”  The crane and frame have the Colt serial number 169206, an early Model 1917 production, which ran from SN 150000 to 301000.  The butt is marked "U.S. ARMY MODEL 1917/NO. 19329," which was the Army serial number for this revolver.  I do not know the significance of the “RA” stamped on the butt of the right grip.  The lanyard swivel is also present.  The barrel is still shiny with very strong rifling.  The action is crisp and the lockup is tight.  It’s a beautiful example of WWI history (95 years old) and also a pleasure to shoot.  This weapon is C&R eligible. Please let me know if you have any questions or would like additional photos.  Buyer will send a USPS money order or certified bank check for the agreed amount + $35 and the name and address of the C&R or FFL (in the continental U.S.) where the pistol will be sent.   If in Alaska or Hawaii, buyer will pay all shipping charges.

title: For Sale:  Sig P250 full-size 9mm barrel/slide assembly with night sights + grip module (2nd gen)
postcontent:
This is a barely used kit for a Sig Sauer P250. Includes everything but the 'fire control unit' and magazine. The FCR is the the internal trigger assembly that can be swapped between frames. It is the 'gun' part that bears a serial number.

Everything is in great shape. You can see slight external wear on the parts of the barrel that contact the slide, and some on the frame where the takedown lever pivots. This is just mild cosmetic stuff from the normal operation of the weapon.

If you have a P250 of any type, these parts will turn it into a full-size 9mm. You can also just use the upper parts (the grips are inexpensive) to change caliber.

These parts are from a second generation kit. The first generation P250's were the ones that were problematic; I've had no issues with my second gen P250; I just prefer the subcompact setup and have no use for these parts.

If you do not have a P250, the FCR's tend to pop up for about $200-250, but don't appear to be regularly available from Sig.

$225 OBO.

title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1917 .45 ACP, WWI U.S. Army Revolver, NRA "Fine" Condition, $1050
postcontent: This is an original, “unmolested” WWI Colt Model 1917 U.S. Army Double Action Revolver in standard .45 ACP. Barrel is marked "COLT D.A. 45" on the left side. Top of barrel reads "COLT'S PT FA. MFG. CO HARTFORD CT. U.S.A..PAT'D AUG. 5 1884. JUNE 5 1900. JULY 4 1905." Bottom of barrel is marked "UNITED STATES PROPERTY." Upper left frame is marked with the Ordnance Department final acceptance mark “GHS”, the unique initials cartouche of Gilbert H. Stewart, a Major in the Army Ordinance Department during WWI and the acting Commander of Springfield Arsenal from January 11, 1918 to March 15, 1918. The Rampart Colt on the left side of the frame is clear and distinct. The “H” acceptance mark from Frances L. Hosmer (a civilian inspector from 1911 through 1925) is present on the rear of the cylinder and inside the crane recess. The left grip frame is also marked with a “G” signifying “government contract.” The crane and frame have the Colt serial number 169206, an early Model 1917 production, which ran from SN 150000 to 301000. The butt is marked "U.S. ARMY MODEL 1917/NO. 19329," which was the Army serial number for this revolver. I do not know the significance of the “RA” stamped on the butt of the right grip. The lanyard swivel is also present. The barrel is still shiny with very strong rifling. The action is crisp and the lockup is tight. It’s a beautiful example of WWI history (95 years old) and also a pleasure to shoot. This weapon is C&R eligible. Buyer will send a USPS money order or certified bank check for the agreed amount + $35 and the name and address of the C&R or FFL (in the continental U.S.) where the pistol will be sent. If in Alaska or Hawaii, buyer will pay all shipping charges.  I accept PayPal, but you must add 3%, the amount PayPal charges me to receive the funds. title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P250 Subcompact 9mm, newer model with night sights.
postcontent:
This is the P250, Sig's modular polymer-framed handgun. Although they got a bit of a bad rap when first released, the newer ('second generation') models such as this one seem to have all the kinks ironed out.

Personally, I think it's a great little handgun. Shoots like a full size but conceals like a sub. The DAO trigger is not for everyone, but I'm pretty fond of it for a concealed carry weapon. No active safeties to mess with, but the double-action travel means you're not going to pull this trigger on accident. 

Only a few hundred rounds through this one. Zero problems- no FTE's, misfeeds, or other issues. Trigger pull has a consistent weight and is very smooth. For me, the grip is very comfortable, even without a pinky rest, and I find it much easier to hold onto than most subcompacts.

Comes with one 12 round mag and one 15 round mag, plus the original case. This was part of the '2sum' set; I have the full size parts listed separately but would be willing to make someone a good deal on the set.

$450 or best offer. Money talks; I'll let this go for a steal if someone has cash in hand and is ready to buy.
